                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-156189 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-hair tag-homosexuality-and-bisexuality tag-kolkata-india tag-san-francisco-calif des-homosexuality-and-bisexuality geo-kolkata-india geo-san-francisco-calif news_keywords-kolkata-india-2 news_keywords-san-francisco-2"
                                id="post-156189">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A New Gay Fairy Tale</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Sandip Roy			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-03-12T07:25:07+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">March 12, 2015 3:25 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">March 12, 2015 3:25 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">KOLKATA, INDIA &#x2014; In the mid &#x2019;90s, about five years after I had moved to the United States, I got rid of the part in my hair. It was the most daring thing I had ever done to my appearance. That side part,
                                        with me since my childhood in India, was the emblem of the well-behaved, well-groomed good boy, and I had carried it diligently into adulthood. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Years later, I moved in with a friend &#x2014; a man who shaved his head and plucked his eyebrows into fine arches of perpetual disdain, wore a ballerina&#x2019;s tutu to a leather street fair with &#xE9;lan and compensated
                                        for late-night deep-fried apple fritter binges by sprinkling flax seeds on his omelet in the morning. For the sake of his privacy, I&#x2019;ll call him R. For six years, R. and I shared a little two-bedroom house
                                        on a steep San Francisco street with an aging, half-blind Chihuahua and an overweight cat. One day R. decided I needed to loosen up a little and took clippers to my head. By the time he had finished, the bathroom
                                        floor was covered with clumps of hair and I had a Mohawk that he proceeded to gel into a stiff mane. I hardly dared look at myself in the mirror, but I was secretly thrilled. I would never have had the guts to do
                                        it myself.</p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/12/opinion/12PRIVATE/12PRIVATE-blog480-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/12/opinion/12PRIVATE/12PRIVATE-blog480-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/12/opinion/12PRIVATE/12PRIVATE-blog480-v2.jpg"
                                                    id="100000003567177" width="480" height="442" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="442">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Jonny Negron</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-156189"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I first moved to San Francisco, a well-meaning aunt said, &#x201C;It&#x2019;s a beautiful city. But be careful of those gays.&#x201D; She could have been warning me about R. He was not just gay, he was extravagantly
                                        so. He could tell you which bathroom stall at Macy&#x2019;s was more cruisey than others and between which hours. He&#x2019;d worked a string of jobs &#x2014; in bathhouses and diners, and cleaning people&#x2019;s
                                        homes. He wrote irate letters to the editor, researched the latest trends in the health care debate and romanced some man he met on the subway &#x2014; all with equal vigor. He was also H.I.V.-positive. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I first met him, about 20 years ago, I regarded him with some caution.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Even though I came from India, supposedly a country sitting on an H.I.V. powder keg, I had never actually knowingly met anyone who was H.I.V.-positive. I had only read about them, classified coldly in pie-charts and
                                        graphs as high-risk groups &#x2014; drug users, homosexuals, prostitutes, long-distance truckers &#x2014; instead of regular people. I regarded R. with caution not because I feared his disease, but because the local
                                        gay weekly was filled with AIDS obituaries and I was afraid to get too attached to anyone whose time seemed limited.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Like many Midwestern gay men of his generation, R. had landed in San Francisco. That one-way ticket, away from Bible Belt towns, conservative families and cornfields, was to me the quintessential trajectory of the American
                                        gay story. R. brought in his wake his own family album of horror stories &#x2014; child sexual abuse, divorce, alcoholism, prison. I listened with wide-eyed na&#xEF;vet&#xE9;. I didn&#x2019;t come from a family
                                        that embraced its gay children with pride and marched down the street in parades with them. But my family seemed so normal compared to his, it was almost boring. It was so placidly happy that I was afraid it would
                                        shatter into pieces if I revealed any dark secret, let alone one about my sexuality. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So we both fashioned lives far away from our biological families. My calls home were all about what I had for dinner, the weather and the weddings of half-forgotten cousins. I told my family little about R. He was like
                                        an alien too difficult to explain. What does he do, they would ask, and I would have no answer. He lived on disability. He often slept till noon and shared stories of vivid dreams involving minor television stars
                                        of the &#x2019;80s. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">R. was my guide to the wild gay San Francisco that was rapidly fading away. Gay pride parades were already filling with baby strollers and sweatpants. But R. still held out like the last stubborn survivor of a different
                                        city.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then one day he did the unthinkable. He decided to leave San Francisco and return home. His mother was aging, struggling to raise two little great-grandsons whose father was in prison. R. felt he was the only one able
                                        to help and it was his responsibility. It caught me completely off guard. I thought familial duty was my bailiwick &#x2014; making that weekly call home, the annual pilgrimage to India, posting birthday cards. I
                                        had thought that living in San Francisco meant reprieve from the duty of being actually physically present in my family&#x2019;s life.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">R. packed his van, turned his back on the City by the Bay and headed home to the stifling town he had once escaped, thereby turning the great fairy tale of the American gay story on its head. All along the way he sent
                                        text messages from diners, rest stops and gas stations. At every moment I expected him to lose his nerve and come barreling back. But he kept going. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was simply the bravest thing I had ever seen anyone do. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We had Hawaiian barbecue on his last night in the city. He didn&#x2019;t think they had that in his hometown. But it&#x2019;s not so bad, he said as if consoling me, as he piled on the potato salad, I think they have
                                        an Indian restaurant now. All he left behind was his battered blue salvaged armchair and a blond wig.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A year later I, too, moved back, to India. When people ask me now why I came home after 20 years, I give them varied reasons. My mother was growing old and the journey to California was hard on her knees. I wanted to
                                        write about the new India. I never tell them about R. But I could not have left the comfort of my San Francisco life, with its happy hour at gay bars and the Hummus Man and Sprouts Lady at organic farmer&#x2019;s
                                        markets, without his showing me the way.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sometimes, late at night in India, when it&#x2019;s the middle of the day in America, we chat on Facebook. I ask his advice about life, love and the virtues of flax seed. Every time I come back to San Francisco I am
                                        tempted to ask R. to come back as well. But sometimes it&#x2019;s best to let the past be the past. I am losing my hair and I know I&#x2019;ll never have a Mohawk again. But I have never returned to that side part,
                                        either.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.bloomsbury.com/author/sandip-roy/">Sandip Roy</a> is a senior editor with Firstpost.com and the author of the novel &#x201C;Don&#x2019;t Let Him Know.&#x201D; </em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
